~ start
[speed=0.5]Snowflakes drifted slowly from the night sky, catching in the light from distant windows.
[speed=0.5]It crunched beneath Andrew’s worn boots as he walked, the sound following him down an alleyway that had no more place left for him.
[speed=0.5]Everyone else has long retreated to the comfort of their homes, with trees that lit brighter than the stars he slept under.
[speed=0.5]The graffiti littering the walls, a far cry to walls strung with Christmas lights and lined with family photos seemed to mock him.
[speed=0.5]He couldn’t help but scoff, amused by his own misery. 
=> END

~ Mem1
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5][i]What did I do to deserve this?[/i]
[speed=0.5]He thought, kicking up a pile of snow as he walked.
[speed=0.5]Occupied by his thoughts, he failed to notice his surroundings until a loud crash reverberated through the narrow alleyway.
[speed=0.5]He turned his head to the source of the sound to see a mangy, old dog scavenging through a knocked over trash bin.
[speed=0.5]It was nose deep into the spilled contents of the bin, sniffing out anything it could eat. 

[speed=0.5]His jaw tightened at the sight, his nose scrunching in disgust. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5][i]Great, now this thing’s in the way.[/i]
[speed=0.5]He cursed under his breath, shoving his cold hands deep into the pockets of his jacket as he approached the cur. 

[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Hey, you!”
[speed=0.5]He snapped, his words sharp and low as he stared down at the dog. Its body tensed up. It does not move.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Why, you little—” 
[speed=0.5]He snapped again, this time louder.
[speed=0.5]The next words died in his mouth when the dog raised its head to meet his gaze.
[speed=0.5]Its ears were flattened against its head. It whimpered, its tail between its legs as it cowered. Its frail body shivering like a leaf fluttering in the wind.

[speed=0.5]And then at that moment, something flickered in the man’s furious gaze.
[speed=0.5]His posture relaxed, the hard lines on his face slowly fading. He stood there, in thought before he sighed.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“You too, huh?” He muttered to himself before shaking his head.
[speed=0.5]He crouched down to its height, coming face to face with the dog. He then placed his hand cautiously on its head before petting it.
[speed=0.5]Its tail wagged eagerly, the corners of its lips curling upwards to resemble a smile.

[speed=0.5]Andrew couldn’t help but laugh at the absurdity of this situation, his breath fogging up in the cold air.
[speed=0.5]Perhaps he had more in common with this dog than he thought. 
=> END

~ Mem2
[speed=0.5]The cold sank deep in slow and merciless, seeping through the sleeves of Andrew’s jacket and numbing his fingers as he fed another piece of scrap into the barrel fire.
[speed=0.5]The flames flickered weakly, bending with each draft that slipped through the broken windows. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“God damn it,”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“We’re going to freeze at this rate.”
[speed=0.5]He slumped back against the wall, exhaling into his hands. The stray dog which he named Max stirred beside him on the mat.
[speed=0.5]It shivered, its ribs visible as it edged closer to the meager warmth the fire provided.
[speed=0.5]It paused as if unsure, then leaned just enough to brush against his leg. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Yeah.. it’s cold, isn’t it buddy?”
[speed=0.5]After a moment, he nudged the mat closer to the barrel with his boot. 
[speed=0.5]Him and the dog sat closer to the fire, the warmth it brought easing the cold winter air ever so slightly.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Don’t get used to it.”
[speed=0.5]He lowered himself to the ground, his eyes drifting back to it. Up close, he could see every rib pressing against its skin. It didn’t even flinch—just watched him, wary, waiting.
[speed=0.5]He clicked his tongue under his breath and dug through his satchel. After a moment, his fingers closed around a small packet of crackers, the last one he’d meant to save.
[speed=0.5]He tore it open, snapping a piece in half before holding one out.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Here,”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: “C’mon. Take it.”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: “Hey—!”
[speed=0.5]It swallowed the cracker in one gulp and crashed straight into him, knocking him onto his back. Before he could shove it off, a wet tongue dragged across his cheek.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Ah! Damn it!”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Alright, alright—”
[speed=0.5]The dog’s tail thumped wildly against his side. He froze for a second… then let out a quiet breath.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“God damn it, Max..”
[speed=0.5]he muttered, almost without thinking.
[speed=0.5]The corners of his mouth twitched upward.
=> END

~ Mem3
[speed=0.5]Andrew woke to the murmur of voices just outside the abandoned building he called home.
[speed=0.5]He rose slowly and crept toward the window, careful to place each step between the groans of the floorboards.
[color=#F0BCD4][shake] [speed=0.5] “I’m telling you, officer, I heard something moving in there,”[/shake][/color]
[speed=0.5]a woman said, her voice tight with fear.
[color=#F0BCD4][speed=0.5][shake] “Last night, too—there was barking. And a fire. Someone’s been staying inside. A squatter, maybe. Who knows what they’ll do?”[/shake] [/color]
[speed=0.5]Andrew’s heart began to pound. He turned. His dog was already awake, sitting upright on the mat, ears alert. Andrew hurried over and crouched beside him.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Come on,”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“We need to go.”
[speed=0.5]Outside, the floor’s faint creaks hadn’t gone unnoticed. One officer glanced at the other and nodded. They moved toward the entrance.
[speed=0.5]Andrew scooped the dog into his arms and scanned the room. No doors. No time. Then he saw it—the fire escape. He rushed to the window, pushing it open just enough to slip the dog through before climbing out after him.
[speed=0.5]Upstairs, the officers reached the hallway and caught sight of movement. One stepped forward—just in time to see Andrew and the dog on the fire escape. Andrew froze, eyes wide. The officers lunged. He slammed the window shut.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Go!”
[speed=0.5]he shouted, scrambling down the metal stairs.The fire escape rattled under their weight as he descended, the officers close behind. At the bottom, Andrew clutched the dog tightly and dropped onto the alley pavement. The ladder above shrieked—and then snapped loose. The officers jumped down after him. Andrew ran.
[speed=0.5]He darted through narrow alleys, cutting corners, not daring to look back until the sounds of pursuit finally faded. Only then did he stop.
[speed=0.5]He leaned against the wall, breath ragged—and suddenly laughed. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Oh… God,”
[speed=0.5]The dog pressed against his leg.
[speed=0.5]Andrew lowered his hands, a tired smile breaking through as he reached down and scratched Max behind his ears.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Yeah.. Yeah, I know.”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“What a way to start the day, huh?”
=> END

~ Mem4
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Max!”
[speed=0.5]He called, chasing after his dog along the snow-covered concrete sidewalk. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Slow down, boy!”
[speed=0.5]His breath came out in ragged bursts.
[speed=0.5]Max didn’t listen. He raced onward, tongue lolling, paws kicking up powders of snow as he tore through the soft white blanket covering the city.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“I can’t—I can’t keep up!”
[speed=0.5]He laughed, bending over with his hands on his knees as he caught his breath, a weary smile tugging on his lips.
[speed=0.5]Up ahead, Max slowed down. Sensing his owner’s exhaustion, he turned and trotted back towards him, tail wagging. He nudged his nose against Andrew’s leg, then looked up at him before springing onto his hind legs and licking his face.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Hey!”
[speed=0.5]He chuckled, putting his hands up to cover his face to shield himself from the barrage of licks. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“C’mon,”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“We should find somewhere to rest. I’m exhausted and I’m pretty sure you are too, huh?”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Aren’t you, boy?” 
[speed=0.5]Max only wagged his tail harder. Andrew laughed.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Yeah.. didn’t think so.” 
[speed=0.5]He shoved his hands into his jacket pockets as he straightened. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Yeah.. didn’t think so.” 
[speed=0.5]“Come on, let’s go. Let’s find somewhere to stay for the night.”
=> END

~ Death
[speed=0.5]It wasn’t long until he and Max sat down at a secluded corner of town.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]:  [speed=0.5]“Damn it.” 
[speed=0.5]He muttered, lowering himself  onto the cold hard ground.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]:  [speed=0.5]“Looks like we’ll have to stay here for the night.” 
[speed=0.5]He grumbled, a light flush dusting his nose and cheeks as the chill settled in. 
[speed=0.5]His fingers fumbled against the fabric of his sleeves, clumsy, as if they were no longer his. A strange warmth crept through his chest despite the sharp bite of the air. He barely seemed to notice.
[speed=0.5]Max inched closer, pressing against him for warmth. 
[speed=0.5]Andrew blinked down at him, a little slower than before, and then let out a soft breath that almost sounded like a laugh. He shrugged his jacket off with stiff movements and draped it over Max.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Here you go, buddy.. You need it more than I do.”
[speed=0.5]His hand scratched behind Max’s ear, his touch lingering and unfocused.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Not like I need it anyway.. I–”
[speed=0.5]He paused, his eyebrows knitting as if lost in thought before a faint smile tugged at his lips.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“I feel warm enough,” 
[speed=0.5]He exhaled softly. 
[speed=0.5]He shifted, curling in closer against Max. His breath came in short, shallow bursts, but he paid it no mind.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“I’m so lucky to have you, buddy.”
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5]“Where would I have been without you?” 
[speed=0.5]He swallowed, words catching in his throat as they came.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]:  [speed=0.5]“I think.. I’m going to rest my eyes for a little bit,”
[speed=0.5]He said, fumbling with his words.
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.5][shake]“I’m tired, Max..”[/shake]
[speed=0.5]His gaze softened as his eyes drifted shut, a quiet, almost peaceful expression settling across his face. 
[color=#1F7A8C]Andrew[/color]: [speed=0.2][shake]“Don’t you go anywhere,”[/shake]
[speed=0.5]He whispered.

[speed=0.3]The next morning, Max stirred.
[speed=0.3]A thin layer of snow dusted Andrew’s hair and clung to his lashes. He laid exactly where he did the night before—too still.

[speed=0.3]Max barked once. Then again. Louder this time.

[speed=0.3]No response.

[speed=0.3]The dog scrambled to his feet, whining as he pawed at Andrew’s chest, licking away at his face as if trying to wake him up. Andrew’s head lolled to the side, his body slack, unmoving.
 
[speed=0.3]Nothing.

[speed=0.3]With a soft whine, Max curled onto Andrew’s side, squeezing beneath his limp arm. He pressed close, seeking for the warmth that was no longer there.

[speed=0.3]And still, he waited.

[speed=0.3]His breathing slowed as the cold crept in, quiet and patient.

[speed=0.3]Max gave one last glance upward before tucking his face against Andrew’s chest.

[speed=0.3]And then, at last, he closed his eyes.
=> END